onically, these are problems that will be solved only by academicsfinding the time to talk and to work together. The essays collected here both critique the culture of speed in the neoliberal university and provide examples of what can be achieved by slowing down, by reclaiming research and research priorities, and by working collaboratively across the disciplines to improve conditions. They are informed both by recent research in medieval studies and by the problematic culture of twenty-first century higher education. The contributions offer very personal approaches to the academic culture of the present moment. Some tackle issues of academic freedom head-on; others more obliquely; but they all have been written as declarations of theacademic freedom that comes with slow thinking, slow reading, slow writing and slow looking and the demonstrations of its benefits. CATHERINE E. KARKOV is Professor and Chair of Art History at the University of Leeds. Contributors: Lara Eggleton, Karen Jolly, Chris Jones, James Paz, Andrew Prescott, Heather Pulliam  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, MedievalxStudy and teaching (Higher)zGreat Britain. 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectives. 0aLearning and scholarship. 0aMiddle AgesxResearch. 0aMiddle AgesxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aNeoliberalism. 0aSlow life movement. 0aUniversities and colleges. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAcademic Culture.  aAcademics.  aAccountability.  aBureaucracy.  aCollaboration.  aEducation.  aHigher Education.  aNeoliberalism.  aResearch.  aResponsibility.  aSlow Looking.  aSlow Reading.  aSlow Thinking.  aSlow Writing.  aTime.1 aEggleton, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJolly, Karen Lo